"context": "Tight credit spreads are a key barometer of risk sentiment and financial conditions: when spreads compress, corporate borrowing costs fall relative to Treasuries, often supporting capital expenditure, refinancing activity, and equity valuations. This story mattered because it showed credit markets largely “looking through” macro/political noise and focusing on carry and fundamentals—potentially encouraging more issuance and leverage. At the same time, ultra-tight spreads can imply limited compensation for downside risks, making credit vulnerable if growth slows, defaults rise, or rates volatility forces a broader deleveraging. ",
